WRITING.TEXT:
 I have never written a book before in my life.  However, I originally read about people earning a little bit of money every month from writing a book with decent enough content (AKA speak coherent English).  
 nbsp;

I underwent a fairly big transformation over the course of a few years from basically no confident to where I am today; so naively confident I go around publishing books with no experience.  
 nbsp;

Ask me anything about the book, my life, my dogs, or absolutely anything else!!  

Edit:  Shit, also [here's the book link](http://www.amazon.com/Building-Confidence-Self-Confidence-Transform-Themselves-ebook/dp/B01498ZESQ/ref=sr_1_8?s=books ie=UTF8 qid=1440884298 sr=1-8 keywords=building+confidence).

 So full disclosure, I have wrote a book on building confidence (which is actually how I came to find /r/Confidence).  I'll shamelessly drop the link [here](http://www.amazon.com/Building-Confidence-Self-Confidence-Transform-Themselves-ebook/dp/B01498ZESQ/ref=sr_1_8?s=books ie=UTF8 qid=1440884298 sr=1-8 keywords=building+confidence)

 nbsp;

But onto the important stuff.  When you're trying to build confidence, people try to do the right thing and get advice.  Sadly, too much of this advice boils down to "love yourself" or "just believe in yourself".  Sure that's PART of the problem.  But I think for many people it's really not that simple (it sure as hell wasn't for me).  I like to take a lot more "scientific" approach to confidence.  You have to figure out what kind of things are preventing you from being confident, and you have to stop doing those things.  When you're insecure, you naturally think in insecure ways.  That's why becoming confident is something that isn't easy to do, *you have to literally change the ways that you think and the way you see things.*  
 nbsp;

To a point, confidence is also a choice.  People will ask me how to become confident, but there still saying things like "I can't get with that girl...".  If you're still saying that stuff, you haven't made a choice to be confident yet.  
 nbsp;

The three absolutely vital pieces of advice I have that I think building confidence boils down to:

 nbsp;

**1.  Realize You Have Value.**  Every person has value, we just often don't realize we do.  Value can be in the form of physical appearance, but it's not restricted to it.  Value can be in humor, value can be in a truly good listener (which isn't nearly as common as you think),  or it can be in any other personality trait.  
 nbsp;

When I was 16, I started working as a shop hand in a local heavy equipment shop.  I became friends with one of the wash bay guys, lets call him Spencer, because that was actually his name.  Over my time there, I very much came to look up to Spencer.  16 year old me was awkward, and insecure; Spencer was everything I admired.  He was talkative, funny, good with women, and extremely confident.  I'll never forget what he said to me one day.
 nbsp;

We're standing in his wash bay talking and cleaning up, and he says to me "Why the fuck would a girl ever get with you?".  I was dumbfounded, I had absolutely no idea how to answer that.  
 nbsp;

"So?" and he looked at me.  
 nbsp;

"Well..." I said, still drawing a blank "I'm pretty nice I think..."
 nbsp;


"Lotta fucking nice guys out there.  Try again"
 nbsp;

I didn't know what to say.  I had never thought about it that far.
 nbsp;

"Well let me ask you a question then.  If you can't even answer that question, how are they supposed to?"
 nbsp;

The two minute conversation stuck with me to this day.  You need to be able to answer that question.  Why would a girl get with you?  I guarantee there are reasons, you just need to figure out what they are.
 nbsp;

**2.  Fake It Till You Make It**

 nbsp;

You don't wait until you reach a point where you think you are confident to start acting like it.  You start acting like it now.  You say what you honestly think.  Walk like you're confident.  If you have to Google how to walk confidently, *then you fucking Google how to walk confidently*.
 nbsp;

When you say something, you say it like you mean it.  Make eye contact.  Hold eye contact.  Tell someone to fuck off if you need to.  

Stand up straight for gods sake.  If you ignore everything else I ever say, stand up straight.  Straighten your spine, broaden your shoulders.  Put your hands at your sides, don't hold them in front of you.  
 nbsp;

Even if you aren't quite there yet, you can convince 95% of others that you are.  Just by acting like you're confident, it will help you *become* more confident.  

 nbsp;

**3.  Be Authentic in Your Personality**

 nbsp;

Don't pretend to be someone your not.  Be who you naturally are.  That doesn't mean that who you are is an insecure loser who should just hole up in your basement forever.  If you aren't funny, then don't try to be funny.  If you aren't naturally a super-talkative person, you don't have to be.  I've known plenty of people who were quiet, and still extremely confident.  
 nbsp;

Being authentic means you speak your mind.  You don't hide your opinions to agree with those around you.  You aren't afraid to be in the minority.  You won't compromise your values.  You aren't afraid to make enemies.  
 nbsp;

You are self-aware.  You know when you were in the wrong, and you can admit to those mistakes and even apologize when it needs it.  If you do apologize, you say it honestly and with purpose.  You *mean* it.  When you say anything, you mean it.  
 nbsp;
 nbsp;

 nbsp;

I hope my take on things can help some people.  If anyone has anything to add or another perspective, then feel free to add onto this!  Of course my own advice is mainly based on my own journey to self-confidence.  Everyone else has a different journey, and so they will have a little bit different advice, so it's always good to hear other perspectives.
 nbsp;

